pla@sktb.demon.co.uk ("Paul L. Allen") writes:

>I know that servers operate as peers, but if servers *were* to post to
>a.s.k it would simplify matters if only one designated server were
>responsible for posting keys.  Yes, you could design a message format so
>other servers didn't re-post, but there's less traffic if only one server
>posts.

I will look into this.  If others have suggestions on this issue, please mail
me and I will post a summary of responses on alt.security.pgp.

>> It would be very easy to set up a UDP based server for the folk on the
>> Internet, or for those who wish to run such a creature internally.

>It might be easy, but is it a good idea?  If, as the original poster
>suggested, the UDP server supplants personally maintained keyrings then I
>would say it is a bad idea.  If the UDP server supplements personally
>maintained rings when a key cannot be found then it might be worthwhile.

I always intended the search order to be private ring before all others.  Next
would be the system ring (or any number of system rings) then UDP based
servers.
